    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2a1f248f_42309f11",
        "filename": "src/core/SkThreadedBMPDevice.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 24,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-03-30T16:19:48Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Please always put {} around every if, for, while, etc.  It protects against bugs like this with no loss of readability:\n\nhttps://www.imperialviolet.org/2014/02/22/applebug.html\n\nSome codebases don\u0027t use {} for short ifs or loops.  That\u0027s a bad idea, but they do need to stay that way for consistency.  Skia is not one of those codebases... please always use {} in Skia, and if you have written or seen any code that doesn\u0027t, I will happily +1 a change to fix them.",
      "revId": "cb6a8605968f5f235f0320e4e712839d7a7df796",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ef992dc6_a21abbba",
        "filename": "src/core/SkThreadedBMPDevice.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 24,
      "author": {
        "id": 5647
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-03-30T19:34:54Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Ok, I definitely saw places where {} are omitted in Skia. I\u0027ll change them when I saw them again :)",
      "parentUuid": "2a1f248f_42309f11",
      "revId": "cb6a8605968f5f235f0320e4e712839d7a7df796",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e87748ea_37a94db2",
        "filename": "src/core/SkThreadedBMPDevice.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 38,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-03-30T16:19:48Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This macro approach seems fine to me.  Two small things can help make macros like this less trouble:\n   1. leave off the trailing semicolon, so that the semicolon the macro\u0027s user naturally writes is required.  That makes it behave more like normal code;\n   2. if your macro introduces new names (like ds), it\u0027s not a bad idea to wrap it in {...} or do { ... } while(false), so that the new names are scoped to your macro.  do {...} while(false) is nice because it makes it possible to enforce that trailing semicolon from point 1.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 38,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 38,
        "endChar": 21
      },
      "revId": "cb6a8605968f5f235f0320e4e712839d7a7df796",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
